args:
King Archeole rises again, and the party must
cut him down to avert Phraeganoth's revival.
Pele is hesitant to harm her one-time friend and
master, but the prince and Celliera convince
her that true loyalty demands she act.
That must be the cause of his revival.
As long as that mana seeps through the\ntear in the space between worlds,\nhe'll rise again and again.
Surely King Archeole is a powerful enough\nfiend to hold an otherworld fragment\nwithin him.
Are we to cross over time and again,\nfighting a war that can never truly be won?
What's yer deal, exactly? You were the one\nwhat asked us to help take this guy out,\nremember?
Yeah! Plus, barreling headlong into\nimpossible tasks is, like, half of what\nwe do anyway.
You swore to stop Phraeganoth's return,\ndid you not?
Is it the thought of killing your king again\nthat has you holding back?
It must be done to save this world.\nI know that...yet it haunts me still.
The cry he gave as he fell still rings loudly\nin my ears.
Besides, I failed to save him from his fate.\nWho am I to become his executioner?
Is it not loyalty to see a king's will done?\nEven if it means an end to all?
Friends don't let friends destroy the world,\nman. That's crazy!
You're running from your own pain.
You can't pretend it's loyalty stopping you\nif you're not willing to face him as he is.
I would know—I was afraid to face my own\nstudents, and so I ran instead.
But {player_name} told me to\ntrust in the love I've put into them.
I care about them—not as I imagine them,\nbut as they ARE. And I'm prepared to face\nthem because my love is sincere.
So isn't facing your king now actually the\ntrue act of loyalty?
That means the black mana will pour\nthrough at an even greater rate!
We ain't lettin' that happen! Hyaaaaaa!
Uh, maybe we shouldn't just dive in\nwithout some kind of—
Well, so much for the element of surprise.
No matter. We planned to fight regardless.
And we can't afford to let him expand that\ntear any further.
You don't have to force yourself, Pele.\nWe'll take this fight.
But ask yourself this: Is it not a vassal's\nduty to right the course of a king who's\nstrayed from his path?
He was wise. Noble. And kind.
Okay, is it just me, or is this chump even\nstronger now?!
Either way, our job is the same! HAAAH!
Heh heh... Ha ha ha! AAAAH HA HA HA!
My king was never one to laugh at the pain\nof another...
Hear me, King Archeole! Your mind has\nbeen swallowed in darkness—let my light\ncast it out now!
The tear should repair itself in time.
If we can keep Phraeganoth inside the\nspace between worlds until then,\nwe should be safe.
But we'll need a fair number of otherworld\nfragments to remain within the rift until\nthat happens.
Therefore, we must fight the king until\nwe've gathered enough.
It sounds like you've made peace with\nthis decision.
I cannot permit my king's noble name to\ngo down in history as a tyrant.
Protecting his legacy is my duty as his\nvassal—and laying him to rest is my duty\nas his friend.
I will waver no more. We must stop him\nand Phraeganoth both.
Let's put an end to this.
